In 2006, my life took an unexpected turn when I suffered a brain aneurysm. I was working at Blue Cross Blue Shield of Michigan, building a stable career, when everything changed.

It began with symptoms I didn’t immediately recognize — a sudden and severe headache, nausea, blurred vision, sensitivity to light, and confusion. At first, I thought it might be a migraine or just stress. But as the pain worsened and I became disoriented, I was taken to the emergency room.

Here are the 2025 eligibility guidelines for Ohio’s Medicare Premium Assistance Program (also known as Medicare Savings Programs or MPAP). These programs help eligible Medicare beneficiaries with limited income and assets pay for Part A/B premiums and other out-of-pocket costs.

✅ Ohio Medicare Premium Assistance Programs (MPAP) & Income Limits

In Ohio, the program is administered through your local Department of Job & Family Services (CDJFS). Eligibility is based on both monthly income and asset limits, which vary slightly from the federal guidelines.

🧾 QMB — Qualified Medicare Beneficiary

  • Covers: Medicare Part A & B premiums, deductibles, coinsurance, and copayments.

  • Ohio Monthly Income Limits:

    • Individual: up to ~$973/month

    • Married couple: up to ~$1,311/month Ohio Department of Insurance+15Morrow County Job and Family Services+15Ohio Medicaid+15Lorain County Job and Family Services+3Warren County Ohio+3ProSeniors+3

  • Asset Limits: Follows federal limits ($9,660 individual / $14,470 couple) Center for Medicare Advocacy+4CMS National Training Program+4Medicare+4

🧾 SLMB — Specified Low-Income Medicare Beneficiary

  • Covers: Medicare Part B premium only.

  • Ohio Monthly Income Limits:

    • Individual: up to ~$1,167/month

    • Married couple: up to ~$1,573/month Center for Medicare Advocacy+2Warren County Ohio+2Morrow County Job and Family Services

  • Same federal asset limits apply ProSeniors+7CMS National Training Program+7medicareresources.org+7

🧾 QI‑1 — Qualifying Individual Program

  • Covers: Medicare Part B premium only.

  • Ohio Monthly Income Limits:

    • Individual: up to ~$1,313/month

    • Married couple: up to ~$1,770/month Cuyahoga County Website+12Morrow County Job and Family Services+12Lorain County Job and Family Services+12

  • Asset thresholds are consistent with federal limits ($9,660 / $14,470) Warren County Ohio+6CMS National Training Program+6National Council on Aging+6

  • Offers limited funds (first‑come, first‑served) and must reapply annually ProSeniors

🔍 Federal Comparisons (2025 Limits)

For reference, federal income thresholds for 2025 are:

ProgramIndividualMarriedCovers
QMB$1,325$1,783Part A & B + cost sharing Investopedia+3Warren County Ohio+3Morrow County Job and Family Services+3
SLMB$1,585$2,135Part B premium only MedicareNational Council on Aging

QDWI$5,302$7,135Part A premium only (for disabled workers) MedicareNational Council on Aging

Ohio income limits are slightly more conservative than federal levels.

🧠 Extra Help

All MPAP participants automatically qualify for the Low‑Income Subsidy (“Extra Help”) to reduce prescription drug costs under Part D plans. This benefit limits prescription costs to about $12.15 per drug in 2025 Warren County Ohio+3Medicare+3Wikipedia+3.

✅ Application Steps (Ohio)

  1. Contact your local County Department of Job & Family Services (CDJFS).

  2. Apply using form ODM‑07216 or through Ohio’s online Medicaid portal.

  3. Submit proof of:

    • Monthly income (e.g. Social Security, wages, pension)

    • Assets (bank statements, property, etc.)

  4. Reapply annually, especially for QI‑1 eligibility.

  5. Call Ohio Medicaid Consumer Hotline at 1-800-324-8680 for help or local assistance Cuyahoga County Website+5ProSeniors+5Warren County Ohio+5Medicare+1Morrow County Job and Family Services.
